North Rift residents took to the streets of Eldoret on Monday in a show of support for governors who led a protest to Moi University against the appointment of acting VC Laban Ayiro.Uasin Gishu's Jackson Mandago and Alex Tolgos of Elgeyo Marakwet led MPs in the protests saying they wanted professor Isaac Kosgey given the position.More of this: [AUDIO] Two governors, MPs storm Moi University over new 'outsider' VC AyiroThe people who demonstrated also said they did not want Ayiro to take over from professor Richard Mibey who retired after 10 years.Ayiro, who is acting deputy vice-chancellor in charge of planning, is to act for three months before the substantive VC is appointed.Read: Prof Laban Ayiro appointed acting Moi University vice-chancellorAmid claims of tribalism in the appointment, the move by the governors and MPs has been condemned by some and supported by others.More than 100 MCAs from Uasin Gishu, Nandi and Trans Nzoia defended them saying their action did not perpetrate tribalism.But the Universities Academic Staff Union asked political leaders to stop interfering with management of universities in the country.UASU secretary at Moi University Jack Abok said the protest by the politicians amounted to serious interference with the independence of the institution.Read: Moi University students condemn protests by Mandago against acting VC Ayiro hiringDeputy President William Ruto also broke his silence on the matter on Sunday saying no one should be denied a chance at leadership based on tribe.He dismissed the politicians' demonstration saying it was reckless and uncalled for."All leaders must act responsibly when dealing with public issues. Public appointments should be made purely on merit, with those who finish top in interviews being given priority," he said.More on this: Ruto breaks silence on Moi University row, terms Mandago protest reckless